{
  "doc_id": "34994",
  "text": "Reverse Hills-Sachs lesion of the shoulder is a rare injury after posterior shoulder dislocation and occurs in less than 2% of shoulder dislocations. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Posterior shoulder dislocation occurs due to high-energy axial loading during internal rotation, anterior elevation and adduction. [CITATION_3] Its most common accompanying lesions are proximal humerus fracture and impaction of the posterior glenoid labrum against the anterior osteochondral surface of the humeral head which may result in a depression fracture, termed as reverse Hill-Sachs lesion. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] We present a case of reverse Hill-Sachs in which the osteochondral depression in the humeral head was repaired by autograft reconstruction without using an internal fixation material.",
